1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ White develops a piece with tempo. What could be more natural? } 3... Qd8
{ The queen has done her job in recovering the pawn, so now retreats to safety. Alternatives like  3...Qd6  and  3...Qa5  are also playable @@StartBracket@@in fact, I used to exclusively play 3...Qa5@@EndBracket@@, but those lines are more complex as Black queen tends to come under attack in various ways. In my experience you will face 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 about 90% of in the Scandinavian and can therefore look forward to having this position after 3... Qd8 on the board quite often against 1. e4! }
4. d4 { Occupying the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is White's most frequently played fifth move, and it is consistent with the well-worn chess maxim of 'knights before bishops.' }
5... Bg4
{ In the 3...Qa5 Scandinavian Black often prefers to develop the light-square bishop to f5. Why, then, does Black prefer g4 here? The answer lies in the pressure on d4. With Black's queen on d8, his light-square bishop creates indirect pressure on d4 and limits the number of attacking setups White can adopt. Moreover, the pin limits White's attacking aspirations with Bf1-c4 and Nf3-e5. }
6. Bc4
{ threatens the typical tactical motif 7.Bxf7+ followed by 8. Ne5+. As a Scandinavian player, you NEED to be aware of this idea! Black should address White's threat with }
6... e6 { , and after } 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 c6 { For instance, } 9. Ne2 Nbd7 10.
O-O Bd6 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 { Here I like } 12... a5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4"]
[Black "6. Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ White develops a piece with tempo. What could be more natural? } 3... Qd8
{ The queen has done her job in recovering the pawn, so now retreats to safety. Alternatives like  3...Qd6  and  3...Qa5  are also playable @@StartBracket@@in fact, I used to exclusively play 3...Qa5@@EndBracket@@, but those lines are more complex as Black queen tends to come under attack in various ways. In my experience you will face 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 about 90% of in the Scandinavian and can therefore look forward to having this position after 3... Qd8 on the board quite often against 1. e4! }
4. d4 { Occupying the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is White's most frequently played fifth move, and it is consistent with the well-worn chess maxim of 'knights before bishops.' }
5... Bg4 { Also possible is the quiet } 6. Be2 { After } 6... e6 7. h3
{ Black faces a decision. On one hand it makes sense for Black to avoid the exchange on f3 since doing so would not lead to the weakening of the d-pawn that White incurs after 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3; however, capturing the knight and playing ...c6 should lead to a safe and acceptable position reminiscent of the main line. }
7... Bxf3
{ 7...Bh5  Initially I preferred this, but after  8.g4  Bg6  9.Ne5  I couldn't find a strict path to equality in this concrete position. This position hasn't been reached too often, but I think it's critical because White has the straightforward plan of h3-h4-h5. Black has a choice:  9...Nbd7  This is safer.   9...Bb4 !?  Sharpest.  10.h4  Interesting is   10.O-O !?  e.g.  Nbd7  11.f4  Bxc3  12.bxc3  +=  10...Nc6  was played in De la Riva Aguado,O  (2460)  -Garcia Ilundain,D  (2495)  Torrevieja 1997.   10...Ne4  looks active, but on  11.Rh3  f6  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Bd3 !  Black is feeling the heat because  13...Nxc3 ?  fails to  14.Bxg6+  Ke7  15.bxc3  +-  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.h5  Be4  Here De la Riva Aguadao played an inferior move.  13.O-O  He would have been better off with   13.f3 !  Bd5  14.h6  g6  15.Bg5  and White would have been clearly better.  10.h4  Nxe5  11.dxe5  Qxd1+  12.Bxd1  Ne4  13.h5  Nxc3  14.hxg6  Nxd1  15.gxf7+   15.Rxh7  Rxh7  16.gxh7  looks crushing at first sight, but Black has the resource  16...Kd7 !  17.h8=Q  Bb4+  and Black will capture on h8.  15...Kxf7  16.Kxd1  Rd8+  17.Ke2  Bc5  White is slightly better. }
8. Bxf3 c6 9. O-O Bd6
{ Accurate, since  9...Nbd7  10.Bf4  would deny Black the use of d6. } 10. Ne2
Nbd7 11. c4 O-O 12. Nc3
{ Maneuvering the knight solely to achieve c2-c4 seems sluggish, but without pawn support and the possibility of future breaks White can't hope to prove much with his bishop pair. }
12... Qc7 13. b3 Rad8 14. Bb2 Rfe8 { Black has a coherent Scandinavian setup. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4"]
[Black "6. h3  and 8. Qd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ White develops a piece with tempo. What could be more natural? } 3... Qd8
{ The queen has done her job in recovering the pawn, so now retreats to safety. Alternatives like  3...Qd6  and  3...Qa5  are also playable @@StartBracket@@in fact, I used to exclusively play 3...Qa5@@EndBracket@@, but those lines are more complex as Black queen tends to come under attack in various ways. In my experience you will face 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 about 90% of in the Scandinavian and can therefore look forward to having this position after 3... Qd8 on the board quite often against 1. e4! }
4. d4 { Occupying the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is White's most frequently played fifth move, and it is consistent with the well-worn chess maxim of 'knights before bishops.' }
5... Bg4
{ In the 3...Qa5 Scandinavian Black often prefers to develop the light-square bishop to f5. Why, then, does Black prefer g4 here? The answer lies in the pressure on d4. With Black's queen on d8, his light-square bishop creates indirect pressure on d4 and limits the number of attacking setups White can adopt. Moreover, the pin limits White's attacking aspirations with Bf1-c4 and Nf3-e5. }
6. h3 { Also most common. } 6... Bxf3
{ When prompted, Black should not hesitate to make this exchange.   6...Bh5  should be avoided because of  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  when the threat of h4-h5 is unpleasant. }
7. Qxf3 c6 { Note that the immediate  7...Qxd4??  fails to  8.Qxb7  +- } 8. Qd3
{ was played by World Champion Magnus Carlsen against an expert in the Qd8 Scandinavian, GM Nikola Djukic. He didn't achieve an opening advantage, however: }
8... e6 9. g3 Nbd7 10. Bg2 Bd6 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 Qc7 13. Rd1 Rad8 14. b3 Rfe8
{ Carlsen,M  (2877)  -Djukic, N  (2521)  Tromso NOR 2014 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4"]
[Black "6. h3 and 8. Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ White develops a piece with tempo. What could be more natural? } 3... Qd8
{ The queen has done her job in recovering the pawn, so now retreats to safety. Alternatives like  3...Qd6  and  3...Qa5  are also playable @@StartBracket@@in fact, I used to exclusively play 3...Qa5@@EndBracket@@, but those lines are more complex as Black queen tends to come under attack in various ways. In my experience you will face 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 about 90% of in the Scandinavian and can therefore look forward to having this position after 3... Qd8 on the board quite often against 1. e4! }
4. d4 { Occupying the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is White's most frequently played fifth move, and it is consistent with the well-worn chess maxim of 'knights before bishops.' }
5... Bg4
{ In the 3...Qa5 Scandinavian Black often prefers to develop the light-square bishop to f5. Why, then, does Black prefer g4 here? The answer lies in the pressure on d4. With Black's queen on d8, his light-square bishop creates indirect pressure on d4 and limits the number of attacking setups White can adopt. Moreover, the pin limits White's attacking aspirations with Bf1-c4 and Nf3-e5. }
6. h3 { Also most common. } 6... Bxf3
{ When prompted, Black should not hesitate to make this exchange. } 7. Qxf3 c6
8. Be3 { Protecting d4. } 8... e6
{ With pawns now established on e6 and c6 Black has established the characteristic 'light-square restriction' structure, which is also present in related openings like the Slav Defense and Caro-Kann Defense. The effect of this pawn arrangement is three-fold:   d4-d5 is discouraged,  White's light-square bishop is restricted, and  Black obtains a convenient anchor for a knight on d5.  As a Scandinavian player I predict you will come to love the solidity this structure offers. }
9. O-O-O
{ An important alternative. In many lines of the Scandinavian @@StartBracket@@especially 3...Qa5 @@EndBracket@@ White's best chances for an advantage are connected with castling queenside, as White's rook on d1 can be a precursor to a d4-d5 break. This line should be studied carefully as it's one of the most direct ways for White to challenge the 3...Qd8 complex. }
9... Bb4
{ Pinpointing the drawback of White's last move. Black threatens to capture on c3 and shatter White's queenside structure. }
10. Ne4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Qd5
{ Hitting e4 and a2 and thereby practically forcing a trade of queens. } 12.
Qxd5 cxd5
{ My choice when I faced the immensely talented GM Jeffery Xiong in the summer of 2015.   12...exd5 !?  may also be playable, though I think White emerges a bit better, e.g.  13.c4   13.Bf4 !?  13...Nd7  Murariu,A  (2501)  -Nanu,C  (2505)  Amara 2007  14.a3  Bd6  15.cxd5  cxd5  16.Bb5  a6  17.Rhe1  O-O-O   17...axb5  18.Bf4+  Be7  19.Bd6  ±  18.Bd3  += }
13. c4 dxc4
{ 13...Nc6 !?  14.c5  a6  15.a3  Ba5  16.Be2  O-O  17.Kb1  Bd8  18.b4  Haznedaroglu,K  (2430)  -Shaw,J  (2449)  Gothenburg 2005. Here it is most accurate to play  18...g6 !  so that  19.h4  can be met by  19...h5  Still, White must be spoiled for choice with his bishop pair and space advantage on the queenside. }
14. Bxc4
{ The most challenging. White recovers the pawn, and Black must be wary of attempts to open the position with d4-d5 or f2-f4-f5. }
14... Nd7 15. Bb3 Bd6 16. f4 O-O 17. Rhf1
{ Erdogdu,M  (2467)  -Djukic,N  (2503)  Novi Sad 2009. Here I like } 17... Nb6
18. f5 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rfc8 20. b3 b5
{ when Black will regain the piece and White's advantage  (if any)  is negligible. As Black you must often be satisfied with such opening conclusions, but if this line bores you feel free to try the more complex 13...Nc6!? instead! }
*

