1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3
{ White develops a piece with tempo. What could be more natural? } 3... Qd8
{ The queen has done her job in recovering the pawn, so now retreats to safety. Alternatives like  3...Qd6  and  3...Qa5  are also playable @@StartBracket@@in fact, I used to exclusively play 3...Qa5@@EndBracket@@, but those lines are more complex as Black queen tends to come under attack in various ways. In my experience you will face 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 about 90% of in the Scandinavian and can therefore look forward to having this position after 3... Qd8 on the board quite often against 1. e4! }
4. d4 { Occupying the center. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is White's most frequently played fifth move, and it is consistent with the well-worn chess maxim of 'knights before bishops.' }
5... Bg4
{ In the 3...Qa5 Scandinavian Black often prefers to develop the light-square bishop to f5. Why, then, does Black prefer g4 here? The answer lies in the pressure on d4. With Black's queen on d8, his light-square bishop creates indirect pressure on d4 and limits the number of attacking setups White can adopt. Moreover, the pin limits White's attacking aspirations with Bf1-c4 and Nf3-e5. }
6. h3 { Also most common. } 6... Bxf3
{ When prompted, Black should not hesitate to make this exchange. } 7. Qxf3 c6
8. Be3 { Protecting d4. } 8... e6
{ With pawns now established on e6 and c6 Black has established the characteristic 'light-square restriction' structure, which is also present in related openings like the Slav Defense and Caro-Kann Defense. The effect of this pawn arrangement is three-fold:   d4-d5 is discouraged,  White's light-square bishop is restricted, and  Black obtains a convenient anchor for a knight on d5.  As a Scandinavian player I predict you will come to love the solidity this structure offers. }
9. Bd3 Nbd7
{ Sometimes it's helpful to think about which moves are 'mandatory' in a position. For Black, ...Nb8-d7 will inevitably be played, as the knight has no business on the a6 square. Therefore Black should play this move immediately and keep the dark-square bishop back for a moment; this bishop could conceivably to go to e7, d6, or b4  (as in the lines with queenside castling from White)  . }
10. O-O Bd6
{ The bishop is ideally situated on this square.   Here  10...Bb4  is weaker since after, say,  11.Ne4  Nxe4  12.Qxe4    Black's bishop is 'unemployed' on b4 and will almost certainly have to return to d6 soon. }
11. Rfe1
{ White has tried a few moves from this position, but the games often take similar paths. }
11... O-O
{ Now we're in middlegame territory. Going forward, Black should have a few goals in mind:   neutralize White's bishop pair @@StartBracket@@if possible @@EndBracket@@,  keep the position closed, @@StartBracket@@don't rush pawn breaks like ...e6-e5 or ...c6-c5; these need to be properly prepared if even played @@EndBracket@@, and  think about staking out territory on the queenside with ...b7-b5 and/or ...a7-a5. 
The following is an illustrative line from a game of our 'model' 3...Qd8 Scandinavian player, GM Nikola Djukic. }
12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 g6
{ More pawns on light squares!   13...Nf6  I believe GM Djukic rejected this because of  14.Qh4  when Black's knight cannot move due to the threat on h7. }
14. Bc4 Re8 15. Rad1 a5 { Grabbing queenside space. } 16. a4 Nb6 17. Bb3 Nd5
18. Bh6
{ White's bishop doesn't achieve much here, though one can already sense some confusion on White's part. These middlegames can be frustrating from the first player's perspective: you have the bishop pair, a space edge, centralized pieces...and there's no clear way forward! Such is the White player's struggle in the Qd8 Scandinavian. }
18... Qf6 19. h4 Bf4
{ Eliminating the bishop pair and leaving White with a rather ineffective light-square bishop thanks to the pawn foundation Black has laid. }
20. Bxf4 Nxf4 *

