[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4"]
[Black "6. h3 and 8. Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8
{ The queen has done her job in recovering the pawn, so now retreats to safety. Alternatives like  3...Qd6  and  3...Qa5  are also playable @@StartBracket@@in fact, I used to exclusively play 3...Qa5@@EndBracket@@, but those lines are more complex as Black queen tends to come under attack in various ways. In my experience you will face 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 about 90% of in the Scandinavian and can therefore look forward to having this position after 3... Qd8 on the board quite often against 1. e4! }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 { Also most common. } 6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Bf4
{ A relatively new try that was recommended by GM John Shaw in his book 'Playing 1. e4 - Caro-Kann, e5 & Minor Lines.' White posts the dark-square bishop actively and dares Black to capture on d4. }
8... e6
{ 8...Qxd4  is not recommended because White obtains a dangerous initiative:  9.Nb5 !  cxb5  10.Bxb5+  Nbd7  11.Qxb7  You don't want anything to do with this position as Black! }
9. O-O-O
{ White claims that he has an improved version of the line 8. Be3 e6 9. O-O-O. In addition to the more active dark-square bishop, an important basis for White's claim is that his queen assists in the defense of White's knight on c3. }
9... Bb4
{ Black should still go ahead and play this irritating move. Up until now I've been painting a rosy picture of White's chances in this line, but the bishop on f4 has a drawback:   10.--  Bxc3  11.Qxc3  Nd5  is in the air. }
10. Ne2
{ I faced this move in a game against GM S.P. Sethuraman in the 2017 PRO Chess League  (an online league with a 15+2 time control)  . }
10... Qd5
{ Attacking f3 and a2 and forcing a favorable queen trade. This is a common occurence when White castles queenside, as we explored in the 8. Be3 e6 9. O-O-O Bb4 lines. }
11. Qxd5 cxd5
{ Black could also consider capturing with the knight, but re-taking toward the center makes the most sense. The half-open c-file may be a source of counterplay for Black. }
12. c3 Be7 13. Ng3 Nc6 14. Bd3 O-O
{ Black had a comfortable game in Sethuraman - Bartholomew, PRO Chess League 2017. I continued with ...Rfc8, with an eye toward expending on the queenside @@StartBracket@@ ...a7-a6, ...b7-b5, possibly with ...Nc6-a5-c4 in mind @@EndBracket@@. I also challenged White's dark-square bishop with ...Nf6-e8 and ...Be7-d6. }
