[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Flank Attack - 5.Bc4 a6"]
[Black "6. a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4
{ I've found that strong players seem to slightly prefer this move over 5. Nf3. A possible explanation is that White's knight may be developed to e2 or White might utilize the f3 square for the queen, and a good player will be aware of these possibilities. }
5... a6
{ A surprising idea that has done much for the credibility of the 3... Qd8 Scandinavian. Black prepares ...b7-b5 and, ideally, ...c7-c5!, temporarily gambiting a pawn. I first became aware of this line by reading 'The 3... Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and Strong' by Daniel Lowinger. Lowinger's book is an excellent resource for aspiring 3... Qd8 Scandinavian players, and I have incorporated some of his findings in to the following analysis. }
6. a4
{ is a natural reaction to control b5, but the tradeoff is that White weakens b4. Black can exploit this with }
6... Nc6 { when the knight is looking to settle on b4. } 7. Nf3
{ is strongly met by } 7... Bg4
{ with pressure. Note that  8.Bxf7+  does not work in this instance because of  8...Kxf7  9.Ne5+  Nxe5. }
*

