[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Flank Attack - 5.Bc4 a6"]
[Black "6. Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4
{ I've found that strong players seem to slightly prefer this move over 5.Nf3. A possible explanation is that White's knight may be developed to e2 or White might utilize the f3 square for the queen, and a good player will be aware of these possibilities. }
5... a6
{ A surprising idea that has done much for the credibility of the 3... Qd8 Scandinavian. Black prepares ...b7-b5 and, ideally, ...c7-c5!, temporarily gambiting a pawn. I first became aware of this line by reading 'The 3... Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and Strong' by Daniel Lowinger. Lowinger's book is an excellent resource for aspiring 3... Qd8 Scandinavian players, and I have incorporated some of his findings in to the following analysis. }
6. Be3
{ Rare but dangerous: White defends d4 and keeps f3 free for his queen, intending long castling. GM Sahaj Grover played this way against me at the 2015 UT Dallas Fall FIDE Open. }
6... e6
{ Amazingly, this was a novelty when I played it.   6...b5?!  is consistent, but after  7.Bb3  Bb7  8.Nf3  e6  9.Qe2  Be7  10.Ne5  O-O  was fine for Black in Martinovic, S @@StartBracket@@2465@@EndBracket@@ -Vukovic, Z @@StartBracket@@2435@@EndBracket@@ Igalo 1994. Here even  7.Be2 !?  could give Black problems after a subsequent Be2-f3 to challenge the black bishop that will arrive on b7.  7.Qf3!  is stronger:  7...Bd7 !?  8.Qxa8   8.Bd3  +=  White has a safe edge if he doesn't want to grab the rook on a8. Black is underdeveloped, and his pawn structure fails to impress.  8...Bc6  9.Qa7  Bxg2  10.Bf4 !  White will emerge from the complications with a better game, as noted by Lowinger. }
7. Qf3
{ GM Grover responds aggressively. By now you may have noticed that lines involving Qd1-f3 and O-O-O are some of White's most ambitious in the 5. Bc4 line. }
7... Nbd7
{ If I could get a 'do-over' I would play this! In the game I played   7...Nc6  , but after  8.O-O-O  Na5 ?!   8...Bd7  came to mind, but I was fearful of  9.d5!  when the stakes are higher for Black with his king in the center.   On  8...Be7  White has the strong reply  9.d5!  exd5  10.Nxd5  when Black will be under heavy fire.   it would have been relatively best for me to continue with  8...Bd6  , though White should obtain a slight advantage. For example:  9.Nge2  Bd7  10.Kb1  O-O  11.Bg5  Be7  12.Rhe1  +=  9.Bd3  Nd5  trying to slow White's center play.  10.Nge2  Be7  11.Nxd5  Qxd5  12.Qg3!?  Qxa2  13.Qxg7  White had the better of it in a sharp position. Grover, S @@StartBracket@@2498@@EndBracket@@ -Bartholomew, J @@StartBracket@@2448@@EndBracket@@, Dallas 2015. }
8. O-O-O Bd6 9. Nge2 Rb8
{ intending ...b7-b5. The pawn may advance all the way to b4 and/or the light-square bishop will make an appearance on b7. }
