1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4
{ I've found that strong players seem to slightly prefer this move over 5. Nf3. A possible explanation is that White's knight may be developed to e2 or White might utilize the f3 square for the queen, and a good player will be aware of these possibilities. }
5... a6
{ A surprising idea that has done much for the credibility of the 3... Qd8 Scandinavian. Black prepares ...b7-b5 and, ideally, ...c7-c5!, temporarily gambiting a pawn. I first became aware of this line by reading 'The 3... Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and Strong' by Daniel Lowinger. Lowinger's book is an excellent resource for aspiring 3... Qd8 Scandinavian players, and I have incorporated some of his findings in to the following analysis. }
6. Bb3 { Prophylaxis against ...b7-b5. } 6... c5
{ Black can execute the main idea anyways ! } 7. Nf3
{ When originally developing this repertoire in late 2015, I saw that this move had been played in only game: Sermek,D  (2532)  -Djukic, N  (2521)  , Portoroz 2005. It looked interesting to me, and I ultimately recommended that Black meet it with e6. While e6 is playable, it completely escaped my attention that }
7... b5
{ simply transposes to our main line in the Flank Attack chapter ! My only excuse is that weird things happen when you analyze the same opening for hours on end 😃 Since it makes no sense to analyze additional variations when the main line is so reliable for Black, I changed this variation to reflect the transposition and I recommend you handle the rare move order 6. Bb3!? c5! 7. Nf3!? in this fashion. Many thanks to the Chessable user 'ZukertortsGhost' for spotting this transposition. }
