{ Let me say upfront: you won't face this move too often. Although the dark-square bishop development is fine, the vast majority of players prefer to develop their kingside instead. Daniel Lowinger devotes nearly 30 pages of analysis to 5. Bg5 in 'The 3... Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and Strong', but I think knowledge of only a few key lines is sufficient against this rare continuation. }
5... h6
{ Helpful: this pawn nudge secures a safe square for Black's light-square bishop in the future @@StartBracket@@... Bc8-f5 and ...Bf5-h7 if need be @@EndBracket@@. Compared to   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bc4  a6  6.Bg5  h6?!  Black need not lose sleep over Bg5xf6 and a quick Qd1-h5, hitting f7. }
6. Bh4 c6 { The natural } 7. Nf3
{ has been played exactly once according to my database. } 7... Bg4
{ Pinning looks like the correct reaction. Black will continue with ...e6-e7, ...Bf8-e7, ... O-O, ...Nb8-d7, etc. }
