[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Miscellaneous Fourths - 4.Nf3"]
[Black "4. g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. g3
{ This kingside fianchetto is a fairly popular plan against 3... Qa5, but in the 3... Qd8 Scandinavian I've seldom encountered it. Still, Black should know how to meet it, as White's plan to exert pressure on the center and Black queenside via the h1-a8 diagonal is a sophisticated approach. }
4... Nf6 5. Bg2 { Now I'll give two possible continuations: } 5... c6
{ A solid reply. Black will develop the bishop outside the chain with .....Bf5 and build our usual Scandinavian setup: ...e6, ...Nbd7, ...Be7/d6/b4, ...0-0, etc. }
6. Nf3 Bf5
{ 6...Bg4  I've often developed the bishop here, but lately I've been re-thinking the wisdom of this square because of the following idea:  7.O-O  e6  8.h3  Bh5  9.d4  Nbd7  10.Re1  Be7  11.Ne2 !  Now Ne2-f4 is coming and Black must part with the light-square bishop. Contrary to the Main Line where Black also parts with the light-square bishop I believe White has more flexibility with his pawn structure @@StartBracket@@the c-pawn is already free@@EndBracket@@ and strong bishop on the h1-a8 diagonal.  11...O-O  12.Nf4 }
7. d4 e6 8. O-O h6
{ Preparing a useful 'cubby hole' for the bishop on h7 in the event of Nf3-h4. }
9. Re1 Be7
{ Oftentimes it's a judgment call whether to put the dark-square bishop on e7 or d6. In this case I somewhat prefer e7 because Black's queen remains connected to d4/d5, and on d6 it would be blunted by the pawns on g2+h2. Oh yes, and   9...Bd6  10.d5!  could be unpleasant! }
10. Ne2 O-O 11. c4 Nbd7 12. Nc3 Re8 13. Bf4 Qb6 14. Qe2 Rad8
{ Black is holding his own despite the disadvantage in space. } *

