1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4 e5
{ This counter-thrust is considered to be the straight-forward equalizer. I also like it because it's in the spirit of 1. e4 d5: destroy White's center! By the way,   3...Nc6  is also fully playable if you're looking for a more complicated game @@StartBracket@@ this could transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3q4/8/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  Bg4  4.Be2  Nc6  @@EndBracket@@. }
4. dxe5 Qxd1+
{ This is the point. Black does not leap at the first available opportunity to recover the pawn; instead, he simply swaps queens, strands White's king in the center, and looks to develop while attacking e5. }
5. Kxd1 Nc6 6. Bb5
{ The most popular try, pinning Black's knight. This move can be met in a few ways, however. }
6... Bd7
{ Simple chess. Black breaks the pin, threatens to capture on e5, and prepares queenside castling. }
7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Nf3 O-O-O+ 9. Nbd2 Ne7
{ The knight will go to either d5 or g6 with more than full compensation for Black. }
