1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3
{ In my opinion this is an underrated line. White does not block his c-pawn as he does with 3. Nc3 and may therefore try for d2-d4, c2-c4, and only then Nb1-c3. The lines I cover in this section are the most forcing in the entire repertoire, so make sure you review them so you aren't caught trying to remember your theory in a sharp position! }
3... Bg4 { Developing and pinning. } 4. Be2 Nc6
{ The most principled and best move. Even though White's setup looks modest, an all-out war for the center is brewing with d2-d4 and c2-c4 on the agenda for White. With 4... Nc6 Black fights for the pivotal d4 square and enables queenside castling. }
5. d4 O-O-O { On } 6. Nc3
{ Black has a wide choice of possible queen moves. I'm going to wax nostalgic for the 3...Qa5 Scandinavian and therefore advocate }
6... Qa5 { e.g. } 7. Be3 e5 8. Nxe5 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Qc4
