1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3
{ In my opinion this is an underrated line. White does not block his c-pawn as he does with 3. Nc3 and may therefore try for d2-d4, c2-c4, and only then Nb1-c3. The lines I cover in this section are the most forcing in the entire repertoire, so make sure you review them so you aren't caught trying to remember your theory in a sharp position! }
3... Bg4 { Developing and pinning. } 4. Be2 Nc6
{ The most principled and best move. Even though White's setup looks modest, an all-out war for the center is brewing with d2-d4 and c2-c4 on the agenda for White. With 4... Nc6 Black fights for the pivotal d4 square and enables queenside castling. }
5. d4 O-O-O 6. c4 Qf5
{ I've played  6...Qa5+ !?  7.Bd2  Qf5  before in an attempt to demonstrate that the White bishop is misplaced on d2. However, 7. Be3 would just transpose, and it's probably not worth the effort to trying to figure out what to do if, say, 8. d5!? }
7. Be3 Bxf3 { Black initiates a forcing sequence. } 8. Bxf3 Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Qe6+
10. Be2 Qe4
{ The alternative is  10...c5!?  I won't analyze this line because very few players will have the time, memory skills, and inclination to memorize two distinct and tactically demanding lines in this system, but if you dislike 10... Qe4 in some way feel free to investigate 10...c5 instead - actually, I feel even the novel  10...Nf6!?  is playable. }
