[White "8. Rare Lines - 1.e4 d5"]
[Black "2. e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ Believe it or not, you will encounter more than a few players who will decline the proffered d-pawn! Maybe they're suspicious of Black's kind gesture? :-@@EndBracket@@ }
2. e5
{ Hardly critical, but occasionally encountered in the wild. Black can expect easy equality here because he has not committed either his c or e-pawn, and chances for either a favorable French or Caro-Kann are high. }
2... c5
{ 2...Bf5  is a viable alternative,  but I usually favor 2...c5. Black plays to control d4 and keeps his light-square bishop flexible @@StartBracket@@it may come to either f5 or g4 @@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bb5 Bd7
{ In 'Play the Scandinavian' GM Bauer calls this move 'more than okay for Black', and I agree. He is threatening a trick that every French player ought to know: 5... Nxe5! }
5. Bxc6 Bxc6 6. e6 { An untested pawn sacrifice, but I suspect Black is fine: }
6... fxe6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Re1 Bd7
{ Black will continue with ...g7-g6, ...Bf8-g7, and ...O-O. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
