[White "8. Rare Lines - 1.e4 d5"]
[Black "2. e5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ Believe it or not, you will encounter more than a few players who will decline the proffered d-pawn! Maybe they're suspicious of Black's kind gesture? : }
2. e5
{ Hardly critical, but occasionally encountered in the wild. Black can expect easy equality here because he has not committed either his c or e-pawn, and chances for either a favorable French or Caro-Kann are high. }
2... c5
{ 2...Bf5 is a viable alternative, but I usually favor 2...c5. Black plays to control d4 and keeps his light-square bishop flexible  (it may come to either f5 or g4)  . }
3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bb5 Bd7
{ In 'Play the Scandinavian' GM Bauer calls this move 'more than okay for Black', and I agree. He is threatening a trick that every French player ought to know: 5... Nxe5! }
5. O-O
{ Just as in the Advance Variation of the French Defense, a bishop developed to b5 can often be exploited tactically. }
5... Nxe5 { Winning a key pawn. Make sure to remember this shot! } 6. Nxe5 Bxb5
7. Qf3 Nf6 *

